{
  "doc_id": "22840",
  "text": "In combination with previous studies in guinea pigs and chinchillas which have suggested that noise-or drug-damaged terminals either recover or regenerate [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , we suggest another hypothesis for the discrepancy between guinea pigs and mice in the profile of ribbon changes as well as SGN degeneration following noise exposure: the intrinsic ability to self-repair following acoustic injury in the inner ear is different across species, and increased synaptic restoration leads to less delayedonset SGN loss in guinea pigs than in mice. At this moment, we have no explanations for why the repair of the ribbon synapses is more effective in guinea pigs than in mice.",
